  "prompt": "Why are there so many people using Quora to answer questions that can easily be found with a simple Google search?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why people might use Quora instead of doing a simple Google search:\n\n1. Personal experiences and insights\n- Users want real-world perspectives, not just factual information\n- Personal stories and anecdotes can provide deeper understanding\n\n2. Community interaction\n- People enjoy engaging with others and discussing topics\n- Quora allows for follow-up questions and conversation\n\n3. Expert perspectives\n- Sometimes professionals or subject matter experts provide nuanced answers\n- Credentials and background of respondents can add credibility\n\n4. Complex or subjective questions\n- Not all queries can be easily answered by a search engine\n- Some topics require interpretation or personal opinion\n\n5. Social validation\n- Upvotes and comments provide a sense of consensus\n- People feel more confident in crowd-sourced information\n\n6. Laziness or habit\n- Some users find it easier to ask a question than search\n- Quora's format can be more engaging than reading search results\n\n7. Desire for current/recent information\n- User-generated content can be more up-to-date\n- Crowd-sourced knowledge can reflect recent developments\n\n8. Entertainment value\n- Reading diverse perspectives can be enjoyable\n- Some answers are humorous or uniquely written\n\nWhile not all Quora questions need to be asked, the platform's design and community encourage this type of interaction.",
